<div class="flex flex-col gap-5">
	<p>
		Digital fashion’s expansion beyond the body has resulted in a new understanding of the body’s scale, surface, and silhouette. The digital stretches what the body can be, letting designers test new proportions, textures, and gestures that the physical world could never hold alone. Garments can behave like light, weather, or code. They can exist as renders, filters, or atmospheres, freed from weight, gravity, or touch.
	</p>
	<p>
		At the same time, these tools intensify material reality. They influence how fabric is printed, cut, engineered, and perceived. Digital abstraction pressures the physical world, generating surfaces and forms that feel composited rather than sewn. Artists move fluidly between simulation and substance, using virtual logic to reorganize physical experience. The paradox is that simulation produces a new material reality. Fashion extends beyond the body, and in doing so, redefines what it means to inhabit the world on- and offline.
	</p>
</div>

